{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601706/1938021901/0343.xml":{"full_text":"LOAN EXPANSION\nIN REALTY IS SEEN\nFinancing for Fields Now\nLacking Funds Urged\nby Executive.\n\u2022ptelal Dispatch to Tha Star.\nCHICAGO, Feb. 19.\u2014Additional\nfinancing for fields of real estate where\nthere is now a dearth of funds was\nforeseen in a speech by Ralph\nH. Cake, Portland, Oreg., savings and\nloan executive, before the North Cen\ntral Conference of the United States\nBuilding and Loan League. He said\nJ that savings, building and loan asso\nciations can expand their lending field\nbeyond the single-family home by\ntaking extraordinary precautions with\nappraisals and provisions that the\nnet revenue is to be paid to the lender\nto help reduoe the loan.\nHe suggested that loans on apart\nment houses, suburban business prop\nerties, downtown business properties'\nand the like be made only by larger\nassociations, with a minimum of prob\nably $2,000,000 in assets. He added\nthat loans on buildings as large as\nfour-family homes can safely be made\nby smaller associations.\n\"We know that other than single\nfamily dwellings are necessary and\nthat money for such loans must be\nmade available,\u201d said the speaker. \u201cTo\nsafeguard our making of such loans\nwe should keep the general attitude\nthat we do not ordinarily make them\nand let the applicant convince us that\nhis particular loan is an exceptionally\ngood risk.\n\"In making apartment loans we can\nhave a provision that all the net rev\nenue is to be paid to the mortgagee.\nIn this way the loan can be reduced\nmuch faster than the minimum re\nquirements for repayment during the\ngood years, and an extra cushion can\nbe built. The same thing can be done\nwith commercial properties and it is\nadvantageous to owners as well as to\nlenders.\n\"On all large properties the mort\ngagee should have at least two in\ndependent appraisers. No man, simply\nbecause he knows values of individual\nhomes, is equipped to value large prop\nerties. So many other considerations\nenter the picture, especially the rev\nenue from the building.\u201d\nHe estimated that the average apart\nment house loan is about 20 times\nas large as the average home loan,\nthat suburban business properties aver\nage from 2 to 8 times the single\nfamily loan and downtown business\nproperty loans from 20 to 200 times\ny the home loan.\nF. H. A. MUST SEE\nPLANS FOR HOME\nRequirement Prior to Beginning\nConstruction Applies to 10\nPer Cent Plan.\nHome builders contemplating use\no( 90 per cent mortgage financing\nmust submit their plans to the Fed\neral Housing Administration for ap- j\nproval prior to the beginning of con\nstruction, Stewart McDonald, Federal\nhousing administrator, explained in\na statement today.\nAn exception will be made in cases\nof dwellings, the construction of\nwhich was begun after January 1,\n1937, and prior to February 4, 1938,\nand which have not been sold or\noccupied since completion. Other im\nportant points to be kept in mind\nwhere 90 per cent mortgage financing\nis planned are:\nThe mortgagor must be the owner\nof the property at the time of the\nInsurance, and the dwelling must be 1\ndesigned principally for single family\nuse, and a down payment of at least\n10 per cent of the appraised value in\ncash or its equivalent must be made.\nThe mortgage must contain com\nplete amortization provisions requir\ning periodic payments by the home\nbuyer not in excess of his reasonable\nability to pay.\nThe F. H. A. must be satisfied that\nthe project is economically sound.\nl _\nNew\nPreston-Built\nHomes\nRepretent the\nUltimate in Value\n4515 Burlington PI. N.W.\nAmerican University Park\nIn one of the most desirable\nnorthwest sections of the city.\nA distinctive center-hall home,\nall brick, 4 bedrooms, 2 baths,\nbreakfast room, attached garage,\nautomatic heat, perfectly insu\nlated always dry easy\nto heat.\nPRICE, *11,500 I\nFinanced to Meet Your Requirements\nOpen Daily and Sunday\nTo /\"Weet: Drive meet on Mass. Ave.\nto +SHi St., right on iSth to Burlina\nton PI., right to Home.\nWINFIELD PRESTON, Inc.\nOWNER fr BUILDER\nCleveland 9824\nA New Home That Meets\nEvery Requirement\u2014and\nModerately Priced\nDETACHED COLONIAL\nFronting on Two Street*\n5613 N. CAPITOL ST. N.W.\nLarge living room with fireplace.\nSpacious (lining room. Modern\nkitchen with latest built-in features\nIncluding electric refrigeration.\nThree fine bedrooms and two com\nplete tiled baths. Large recreation\nroom. Automatic heat. Large land\nscaped lot.\nOut New Hamvthire Ave. N.W. to\nNorth Capitol St. and home.\nOpen 9 A.M. to 9 F.M. Daily\n\nf IBEITZELLi^\nL_ i\nUS555555S55555555553E2232\nPlan of Lumber Industry Home\nLiving Boom\nI3'0\"*I7'3'\u2018\nVest. c>-\u00b0\n\nPerfect Home\n(Continued Prom First Page.)\ncago. reveals a livable arrangement\nof living room, dinette, kitchen, two\nbedrooms and bath, with heating plant\nand laundry situated in a utility room\nbelow the level of the main floor. The\ngarage is detached.\nContract for the construction cf\nthe home has been awarded to A. C.\nMcMillen of Clarendon. Va., and\nbuilding materials are being supplied\nby Murphy Ames, retail lumber\ndealers of Arlington The mortgage\nwill be held by the First Federal\nLoan Association of Arlington, Va.\nW. W. Woodbridge, secretary-man\nager of the Red Cedar Shingle Bureau.\nwhich includes in ius membership 95\nper cent of all red cedar shingle man\nufacturers in the United States, has\nbeen in Washington for several days,\nworking out details of erecting the\ndemonstration dwelling with F. H. A.\nofficials.\n\nLinseed Oil Before Putty.\nWhen filling cracks in a floor pre\nparatory to painting, putty or prepared\ncrack fillet may be used. Before\nusing putty, apply linseed oil to the\nedge of cracks with a small brush.\nThis will prevent the dry edges of the\nboards absorbing the oil from the\nputty and leaving it to dry and crum\nble away.\nI Price, *8,450\nEASY\nTERMS\n116 SOUTHWJCK ST.\nI Huntington Terrace. Bethesda. Md.\nUNUSUAL VALUE\nTHIS charming\nI 'new Colonial Drive to\nhome contains .1 d l t a\nI bedrooms rj Bank of Be\namply large for\ntwin beds> large tnesno, out\ntiled bathroom r\\jj r\nwith shower spa- heorge\u2022\nrious living and p j\ndining rooms. *oa K o Q a\ncheerful kitchen. \u00bbi \u2022/_.\nbeautiful entrance 1 /2 40\nhall, floored attic. L\nbright dry base- bouthwtc h\nment. automatic\nh e at lot big 1\nenough to provide \u201eM c\u201e.,}A\u2122.,> A\nvegetable and onbouthwick\nflower garden: de- Ktrret in \\'n\nt ached garage. ,0 A\nWell worth your /I*\ninspection.\nOpen for Your Approval 10 to 0 PM.\nMARLOW-BEECH CORP.\nWisconsin 5598\nLight and Warmth in Room.\nSuggesting light and warmth in a\nnortheast bedroom, an ivory-painted\nceiling meets four walls of pale pink,\nsponge-stippled with deep pink, pale\ngreen and cream. The woodwork is\npainted cream. On the floor is a sand\ncolored rug. Ease draperies over\ncream-colored curtains and rose deco\nrations on the ivory-painted furniture\nadd a cheerful note. Turquoise acces\nsories give added distinction.\nThe National Retail Lumber\nDealers\u2019 Association has ob\ntained from the Federal Hous\ning Administration the first\nmortgage insurance commit\nment, under the revised Hous\ning Act, for construction of\nthis five-room demonstration\ndwelling in nearby Arlington\nCounty. It will be located at\nIllinois street and Eleventh\nroad north, in the Lacey For\nests section. The home will\nbe the first in a Nation-wide\nsmall homes campaign spon\nsored by 20,000 retail lumber\nmerchants.\nP b\ni 3\n\nG\nI\nG\nI\n\nTHE MAN\nWHO TOLD\nYOU\nI\nNot to buy a HOME\nbecame PRICES WERE\nCOMING DOWN, WAS\nWRONG AS USUAL.\nRollingwogd\nIs a beautiful suburb of people who DO THEIR\nOWN thinking and know when to buy.\nThey include architects, Government people, lawyers, Bureau\nof Standards experts, business people and reol estate men.\nHere you will find homes that meet your require\nments at prices you will pay. See 602 and 611\nRoiling Road or 612 and 614 Leland St. Also see\n6514 and 6538 Maple Ave., hich is in our Forest\nSection of Chevy Chase, west of Conn. Ave. and\nnorth of Bradley Lane.\nTO INSPECT:\nDrive out through Rock Creek Park (Beach Drive) to LELAND\nSt. one square to Roiling Road, then to top of hill or out Conn.\nAve. to Woodbine St., right 2 squares to Brookville Road,\nthen left to Leland St., through Leland to Rolling Road.\nNEW\nI in\ni\nI\n\n\nI\n\nI\n\nHOMES\n*9250\nDrive out Wisconsin Ave. to\nd Bradley Lane, turn left 2\n1 blocks to Leland St., right to\nhome.\n1\nj Carefree Comfort\n1 With Modern Goa\nAppliances\nI\n4824 Lelaid St., Belbesda, Md.\nThis beautiful home, located on a 60-foot-wide boule\nvard, has one of the most beautiful settings obtainable.\nIt contains exceptionally large rooms with plenty of\nwall space, lovely fixtures, beautiful flooring and hard\nware. Modern de luxe kitchen with plenty of cabinet\nspace. Large trunk closets, built-in garage. Of course,\nit is insulated, weather-stripped, screened and caulked.\nGEO. A. SACKS, be. R. O. Phillips, Agent\n6600 Wisconsin Ave. N.W. Wisconsin 6663\nGAIN IN MATERIAL\nSALES EXPECTED\n\nSurvey of Retail Dealers in\nBuilding Field Shows\nFaith in 1938.\n0\nIncreased business in the building\nmaterials field during 1938 is ex\npected by more than two-thirds of\nthe retail dealers who filled out\nquestionnaires at 13 housing \"clinics\u201d\nRecently conducted by a large b\u2019lilding\nmaterials manufacturer, in as many\nkey cities of the East, Midwest and\nSouth\nThe \"clinics\u201d were attended by a\ntotal of 2,582 leading building jna\nterials dealers, representing 1,837 dif\nferent firms with a combined sales\nvolume during 1937 of $135,811,770.\nRepresentatives of 835 firms com\npleted the questionnaires, which were\ndesigned to disclose current business\noutlook and philosophy.\nOnly 22 Per Cent Expect Slump.\nAccording to results just tabulated,\n65 per cent of the dealers expected\nthe sales trend for 1938 would be up\nward, 22 per cent expected a slump\nand the other 13 per cent were non\ncommital on this point.\nGross profits for the year would\nalso be higher according to 46 per\ncent, although 36 per cent expected\nthat they would be lower. As to net\nprofits, 43 per cent expected a rise\nand 39 per cent expected a drop.\nOn the basis of these expectations,\n58 per cent of the firms indicated\nthat they were planning to increase\nadvertising expenditures, which aver\naged 1.68 per cent of sales in 1937\nand 36 per cent were going to in\ncrease their sales foices.\n1937 Sales Gain.\nThe survey also showed that de\nspite a slackening off in building\nactivity during the last half of 1937,\nlast year's sales averaged 20.5 per\ncent more than in 1936 with the\ngreatest increase\u201432 per cent\u2014being\nrecorded in the Pittsburgh area.\nThat operations in the contracting\nfield by building material dealers is\nfairly extensive was also disclosed by\nthe figures which showed that 44\nper cent did roofing and sidewall\nJobs; 40 per cent contracted for home\nImprovements and 30 per cent took\ncontracts for new homes.\nSECOND-CLASS STAIRS\nPROVE POOR ECONOMY\nTo build anything but a first-class\nstairway is unwise and therefore poor\neconomy. The stairs in a house are\nimportant from the standpoint of both\nuse and decoration.\nThe results of poor stair building\nare many, aggravating, and conspicu\nout. Squeaky or sagging treads, loose\nhand rails or newels, rattling balusters,\nopen Joints, all are the result of im\nproper construction.\nIn a properly built stair the wall\nstring (that sloping member at the\nwall against which the treads and\nrisers butt) is cut so that the treads\nand risers slip in from the back. The\ngrooves into which they fit are tapered\nso that wedges can be put in, driven\nup tight, and glued to hold them se\ncurely in place. The treads and risers\nare interlocked where they meet by\nmeans of a tongue and groove.\nKENWOOD\nNew\nHomes\nNow\non\nExhibit\nIn\nKenwood\n\nThese\nAre\nElectric\nKitchen\nHealth\nHomes\n\n'J\u2019HE Early American house attains three bedrooms, two ot which are over 20 feet in length, bcL\nroom or library on first floor with complete bath, also living room, dining room, butler's pantry\nand kitchen, game room, servant's room and bath and two-car garage.\n'J\u2019HE Formal New England Colonial house contains six large bedrooms, library, living room, dining room,\nbutler's pantry and kitchen, recreation room, maid's room and bath ond two-car garage.\nJ^ENWOOD is often referred to as a community of outstanding architecture and most rigid restrictions\nIt's golf course, swimming pool and tennis courts add to the joy of living here.\nKennedy-Chamberlin Development Co.\nKenwood Office: Kennedy Drive and Chamberlin Ave.\u2014Wisconsin 4425\nTo reach Kenwood, drive out Connecticut Ave. to Chevy Chase Circle west on Grafton street thmunh\nto \"iZnnnoS oZZ't?\u00b0r' ZZ\u00b0>Lt 'ncon.ie Avenue to Dorset Avenue, west on Dorset Avenue through Somerset\n^rcnMf to Bradley Lane and u:est on Bradley Lane to Kenwood.\nt. f\nI\n\nintroducing\na/rfje/a\nsouthern Avenue at 34th s.e.\nDISTINCTIVE SMALL HOMES\nIN A PLANNED COMMUNITY\n3409 FAIRHILL DRIVE\nA delightfully different 5-room brick home\u2014completely in- 4242 AgA\nsulated with Johns-Manville rock wool and Bryant Air Con- tSvatVOU\nditioned with automatic gas heat. Beautiful bath with A\nshower\u2014full b^ement with laundry trays\u2014second floor\nplanned for 2 bedrooms and bath or recreation room. 42ft /f 0*42\nWooded lot 60x100 feet.\n1 J\nNew Homes that Combine the Artistic zvith the\nPractical, Within the Average Family's Budget\no\nThe opening of Fairfield today inaugurates a new era in modern housing for the family of mod\nerate means. Here a carefully restricted community Is being developed each an individual design,\nartistic in conception and planned to afford the maximum livability at minimum cost. On a high,\nrolling, wooded terrain, overlooking a charming countryside, Fairfield is the environment you have\npictured as ideal for your family and living here is easily within your budget. While surpris\ningly moderate in cost, these homes are quality built In every detail. Copper pipes and flashings,\nhardwood floqrs throughout, screen* weatherstripping, slate and Johns-Manville roofs\u2014these are\nbut a few of the fine features that assure you a better home for your money in Fairfield.\n\u201cCarefree-Comfort With modern Ga* Appliance*\u201d j\nntMECTlONS: Drive out Designed and tanned by DANIEL, DANIEL DANIEL I I\nPennsylvania Ave. S.E. across _ ere _ S\nSTANDARD PROPERTIES 1\n213 WOODWARD BLDG. S.I., NATIONAL 5513\nright on jjtft St. to Fairfield. or EMERSON 7117\n:_\n.1\n122o\\\nGarfield Place 1\nI! Woodside, Maryland 1\ny An outstanding value eh\n3 in quality built brick ra\nColonial home of 6 i\n1 rooms and bath. Brick\nI construction with slate j|\nj| roof, thoroughly mod-\nern and a real home, ra\nLarge lot, 60x160. B\nAutomatic heat by gas, I\nwith gas refrigeratqr 2\nand range. Carefree\ncomfort with modern\ngas appliances. I|\n(Drive north on Georgia g\nAvenue past the intereec- 3\ntion, right about of a fc?\nmile to Garfield Street, H\nturn left and follow diree\u2022 S\ntion eigne.) fs\n*8,950\nJ. Wesley\nI Buchanan\n1732 K St. N.W.\nMet 1143 /3\nW it s i f\n1 ]hese Are Homes 1\nVVoshington's I\nUesf Resident,ol\nSections f\nI 62,5 Piney Brooch if\n0 Rood |5?\nJ ilS,*a:c If\nJE\" m'l.S Iff\nf ^ns Ui*\n2 Jlndscapecj jo*8 niceJy\ns*,75\u00a9 I\n1^12 Underwood Ifif\n8; S'. N.W.\n0 1 Block From ]fi<h e. ^g\nI\nI,1 covered *\u00a3\u00ae?hhom,r S\nffr^es thic ll\u00ab oalr 0*\nI halj DlanShJl!!ur center- 3\n*?f Pl^arrani P0l\u00b0nial w\n3 I- baths o,l r00m* S'\n9 tioned heat it.^,rv'con<li-\nI jisu, I\n8 wb&l &f\u00abn I\ntoo of hilt r?.rdr> Rond ES\na house street R